# Multilingual (i18n)

The site must support multiple languages. Design for it from the start; **do not add translations unless the user explicitly asks**.

## Default behavior

- Ship **English only** until the user requests a locale or full translation pass
- Do not install i18n libraries, locale switchers, or extra language files proactively
- Do not translate existing copy into other languages on your own

## Target locales

The site will be translated into these languages (English is the source of truth):

| Code | Language   |
|------|------------|
| `en` | English *(default)* |
| `de` | German     |
| `es` | Spanish    |
| `lt` | Lithuanian |
| `ro` | Romanian   |
| `hu` | Hungarian  |
| `tr` | Turkish    |
| `el` | Greek      |
| `th` | Thai       |

Do not add any of these translations until explicitly instructed for a specific locale.

## How to build i18n-ready now

- Keep user-facing strings out of JSX when practical — use `src/data/content.ts` or locale-ready modules with stable keys
- Prefer keyed content shapes, e.g. `{ title: '...', description: '...' }`, not anonymous strings scattered in components
- Avoid string concatenation for sentences; use full phrases per key so translators can reorder words
- Leave room for longer copy (German, Hungarian, etc.) — avoid fixed widths that break with longer text
- Set `lang="en"` on `<html>` for now; plan to make it dynamic later
- Plan for locale-aware URLs (e.g. `/en/...`, `/hu/...`) or a query/subdomain strategy — pick one when implementing routing, do not guess without user input

## When the user asks to translate

- Confirm target locale(s) and scope (single section vs full site)
- Add or extend locale files / i18n setup only for requested languages
- Keep English as the source of truth unless told otherwise
- Update SEO metadata (`title`, `description`, Open Graph) per locale when translating pages

## Do not

- Hardcode language-specific logic in components (no `if (lang === 'hu')` in UI code)
- Mix translated and untranslated strings in the same visible section
- Auto-translate marketing copy without explicit approval
